                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-157844 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-mary-magdalene tag-theater per-mary-magdalene des-theater news_keywords-theater" id="post-157844">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">On Whoredom, Demonic Possession and Penitence</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Julia Elliott			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-08-13T07:21:05+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 13, 2015 3:21 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 13, 2015 3:21 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I appeared at the dress rehearsal for &#x201C;Life of Christ&#x201D; wearing a pink sheet toga-style, Miss K., the Methodist choir director, took me aside.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I want you to dress like a prostitute,&#x201D; she said.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I am dressed like a prostitute &#x2014; from the biblical times.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What I mean is a contemporary whore.&#x201D; She put some gusto into the final word, her small eyes widening behind the lenses of her hideous glasses. Miss K. had the unadorned face of a Puritan. She ruled both
                                        the children&#x2019;s and the adult choirs with an iron fist, and my father, who&#x2019;d been cast as Judas for the Last Supper scene, called her a &#x201C;fascist.&#x201D; But she dreamed up dramatic extravaganzas
                                        that jolted her audience out of its habitual stupor.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-157844"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/opinion/6private/6private-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/opinion/6private/6private-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/opinion/6private/6private-blog480.jpg" id="100000003838785"
                                                    width="480" height="666" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="666">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Lala Albert</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Miss K. had gone with what biblical scholars call the &#x201C;composite Magdalene,&#x201D; the conflation of Mary Magdalene with another scriptural Mary and the sinful foot-washer from the book of Luke. Pope Gregory
                                        I popularized the idea of Magdalene as a repentant sinner, performing one of the most dramatic slut-shaming maneuvers in history, robbing Magdalene of her apostle status, and heating up the Messianic narrative with
                                        some sexy penitence.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Miss K. asked me to think hard about repentant sluts. She informed me that of the seven devils cast out of Magdalene, one of them was the &#x201C;Demon of Lust.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over the next week, I contemplated whoredom, demonic possession and penitence, weighty topics for a 12-year-old with no breasts whatsoever. I was a scrawny, hyper redhead, one of the pariahs in my class who hadn&#x2019;t
                                        hit puberty, a girl who &#x201C;talked funny,&#x201D; didn&#x2019;t tan, and had zero interest in sports. Despite my freakazoid status, I was in love with my middle school&#x2019;s reigning heartthrob jock, L.&#xAD;F.,
                                        who&#x2019;d been cast as Christ in the children&#x2019;s portion of the play. That summer I was reading &#x201C;Crime and Punishment&#x201D; and some torrid bodice rippers I&#x2019;d pinched from my grandmother&#x2019;s
                                        stash. And L.&#xAD;F., who taunted me with insults like &#x201C;mosquito-bite boobs,&#x201D; frequently appeared in my fantasies. I resented the South Carolina backwater that caged and misunderstood me. Trapped
                                        in my stunted body, I longed for the transformation of adolescence, which would turn me into some shimmering winged creature who would flutter away.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To enhance my suffering, Dad was one of the weirdest men in town, an elementary school principal who chain-smoked and quoted Dostoyevsky. A difficult childhood had scarred him for life. He was blind in one eye from
                                        a BB gun accident and missing his front teeth from a motorcycle stunt. That summer, his false teeth glinted in the depths of a lush, black beard that seemed like an externalization of his inner torments. Because
                                        of the beard, Miss K. had cornered him at church and said, &#x201C;you are the perfect Judas.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During the week that I took it upon myself to understand holy whoredom, Dad&#x2019;s torments reached a fevered pitch. He wanted to shave off his itchy beard and quit the play, but Miss K. prodded him onward. The beard
                                        grew wilder, as though it would soon fill our house with hairy darkness, suffocating us all. My longing for escape formed a knot in my stomach. I feared that the miracle of womanhood would never touch me, that I&#x2019;d
                                        forever be a freckled troll child, trapped in a hot house with a troubled Judas.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the Last Supper, Jesus had dropped a doozy on his disciples &#x2014; I say unto you, that one of you shall betray me &#x2014; and Dad had taken this to heart. He paced around smoking, clutching his tattered script
                                        and muttering, &#x201C;Is it I?&#x201D; My little brothers staggered behind him, mocking his lines.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mom hissed, &#x201C;I&#x2019;m so sick of Judas I could scream.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I couldn&#x2019;t go to Mom for advice on whoredom, demonic possession and penitence. Fortunately, I&#x2019;d watched &#x201C;The Exorcist&#x201D; six times, so I knew a thing or two about possession. Because Regan,
                                        the bedeviled child in the film, was 12, I identified with her foul-mouthed adolescent rage and sexual frustration. Locked in my bedroom, practicing the throes of demonic possession, I imagined stern priests hovering
                                        over me, obsessed with my vile, pubescent body. Puberty was like a demon rocking through your body, changing it from the inside out. Nothing could stop it: not even two repressed priests armed with ancient poems
                                        and holy water. As I dressed for the play, slipping into Mom&#x2019;s castoff cocktail dress, I wondered if L.&#xAD;F. would be impressed.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the way to the church, Dad sighed and studied his script. Mom rolled her eyes, and neither of them commented on my slut garb. As I tottered around backstage in three-inch pumps, disciples from the Last Supper flirted
                                        with me. A mustachioed man winked and said, &#x201C;come give your uncle some sugar.&#x201D; Though flattered, I felt a sick twist in my gut. I tried to catch Dad&#x2019;s eye, but he was hunched in a corner, muttering
                                        his lines.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At last, Miss K. summoned me onto stage with a scrap of scripture: &#x201C;And of certain women, healed of evil spirits and infirmities, came Mary Magdalene, out of whom went seven devils.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I strutted into lurid red light, owning my sluttiness, my hair teased big, my face done up in full glam mode. The audience gasped. When I dropped onto all fours and grunted like a hog, they fell into stunned silence.
                                        Rolling, flailing, I croaked demonic pig Latin. L.&#xAD;F. walked toward me in his holy robes, trying not to crack up. He knelt before me. At the dress rehearsal, I&#x2019;d allowed him to place his hands upon my
                                        shoulders and cast the demons from me with an easy shove. But this time I kept at it, making him work for it, groaning until the smug smirk left his handsome face and he looked genuinely freaked. When he finally
                                        got a good grip, I imagined the devil leaving my body. I remembered a scene from &#x201C;The Exorcist,&#x201D; when Pazuzu appeared on Regan&#x2019;s bed, gargoyle-faced but boasting an impressive set of wings.
                                        I swooned like a romance heroine, falling back into Christ&#x2019;s ripped arms. I imagined the demon flitting over the heads of the congregation, its furious wings spraying silver sparks.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stage went dark again and then black lights popped on. Like a hot slut in a metal video, I crawled toward L.&#xAD;F., who now sat at a table sipping fake wine. When I knelt before him, he smirked through his fake
                                        beard. He almost kicked me in the chin. But I whipped out my bottle of Poison perfume and anointed his feet. I wept, dribbling the despair of my harlotries onto the dirty feet of a boy I both hated and loved. A
                                        nervous cough echoed as I dried Christ&#x2019;s feet with my hair.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I blinked as light flooded the stage. I glanced toward Miss K., feeling admiration for the wingspan of her ambition, wondering if she, too, dreamed of escape. With a sly smile, she granted her approval, letting me know
                                        that I had embodied the jezebel with passion and depth.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And then she went crazy on the organ, playing &#x201C;Jubilee.&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.juliaelliott.net/home/about-julia-elliott/">Julia Elliott</a> is the author of the story collection &#x201C;The Wilds&#x201D; and the forthcoming novel &#x201C;The New and Improved Romie Futch.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
